The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) reported on its Web site on Feb. 20 that there are signs of community-based transmission of the new coronavirus in many countries and regions. The information appeared in the network's travel related information for the 2019 new coronavirus, although the U.S. CDC determined that there had been significant transmission in Japan, Singapore, South Korea, Thailand, Vietnam, Taiwan, and other places, but it's not up to the standards of a travel alert.

The US CDC explained that the so-called "community transmission" means that there are cases of infection with the virus, but some cases of infection, such as the location of infection, infection routes unknown. The US CDC's "Watch" travel alert for the Hong Kong region, the lowest level, does not recommend cancelling or postponing a visit, but warns travelers to avoid contact with sick people and to wash their hands regularly or use alcohol-based handrub.

At the same time, the South Korean government announced on February 20, the new coronavirus has broken through the country's epidemic prevention network, there are signs of the spread of community infection. In Taegu, South Korea, a 61-year-old woman became a super-spreader. The local government in Daegu urged its 2.5 million residents to stay at home.

Taegu is South Korea's fourth largest city in the southeast, with a population density of 2,818 people per square kilometre, after Seoul, Busan and Incheon. According to the latest statistics, South Korea 20 pm added 22 new cases of pneumonia, making the total number of confirmed cases reached 104. South Korea also had its first death.
